node.text:
.
I happen to drive by the dump site I use to goto 2-3 day a week, so I figure I share an insight into my past.
.
15 years ago, I bought my first company truck at the age of 24. Although I was the boss, I was also the truck driver and trash hauler. When you are a small company you have to do everything and that includes picking up construction debris, hauling, and driving to the dump. I remember how awful the trash dump smells, but it helps you appreciate the better things in life.
.
I didn’t start off working at a designer’s fancy office or showroom wearing fancy clothes and looking pretty. Just a young kid with a baseball cap chasing a big dream doing whatever I can to earn a buck. Sometimes people see the image of success but don’t realize the sweat and tears behind the scenes.
. 
📲 contact us @dannywangdesign for your creative interior exterior design build
.
.
.
.
.

DIY mosaic table (dm me if this is your video for credit)
.
⚠️These are purely my opinions only. If you don’t agree we can still be friends.
.
Pros: 
1) Reuse possibly left over material or broken material 
2) creates a custom look
3) doesn’t break the bank with this diy
.
Cons:
1) time consuming 
2) requires some concrete skill 
3) if not done correctly some of the tile edges can be sharp
.
Let me know what you think or if I missed anything. DIY or D-I-Why?
.

.
DIY Pool by @5.min.crafts 
.
⚠️These are purely my opinions only. If you don’t agree we can still be friends.
.
Pros: 
1) Relatively easy DIY
2) Accessible material
3) Fastest way to get a pool this summer 
.
Cons: 
1) Pallet is expensive. This might cost as much as a nice portable jacuzzi 
2) pallets might not be strong enough to hold the water and the hydrostatic pressure 
3) requires quite a bit of work 
.
Let me know what you think or if I missed anything. DIY or D-I-Why?
.
.
.
.
.

.

1) Good for viral videos

3) Unique and sustainable idea with the recycled glass bottles
.
Cons: 
1) structurally unsafe 
2) would leak 
3) diy that requires a lot of work
4) waste of a lot of time 
.
Let me know what you think or if I missed anything. DIY or D-I-Why?
.

node.text:
W A Y S
There are many ways to spruce up a room. You can use this as a list to look at when deciding what to do with a room. I broke down the number of things we did to spruce it up. Use as a reference when deciding what you can do with your own space.
.
1. Paint- we repainted to a beige tone color to match rest of the house 
2. Coffered ceiling- gave it coffered ceiling treatment to give it more details. Make it look more fancy.
3. Wall paneling/treatment - we paneled the wall with wood panels around the window then installed custom mirrored tiles to make the room look bigger.
4. Flooring- replaced carpet with marble tiles 
5. Windows- removed windows on the right side and replaced with bifold doors to give access to the California room outside. 
6. Wine column- added 2 wine column for frame in the dining room and have display and storage for wine bottles
7. Window treatment-roller shades that retract to cover the windows. Drapes in front of the new door we installed.
8. Furniture- Gotta have them
9. Art and decor pieces
10. Lighting- custom chandelier overhang the dining table.
.
Let me know which number you think made the most impact.
.
📲contact us @dannywangdesign for your interior exterior design or build needs.
.
.
.
.
.
#luxury #design #interiordesign #mansion #home #architecture #luxurylifestyle #interior #modernhome #beforeandafter

node.text:
P O T E N T I A L
Every space has a potential to be great. Often times I go see a property and notice they become neglected because it hasn’t been maintained properly and the homeowners simply gave up on the up keep. Then it becomes not used and just they just pretend the outside space doesn’t exist anymore.
.
In reality it just needs a little love. Like this project, we have a yard with patches of dead grass that doesn’t get used and looks forgotten. We came in added a pool and spa and gave it a little transformation. Now it’s more functional and looks so much better.
.
📲 contact us @dannywangdesign for your interior exterior design or build needs
.
.
.
.
.

node.text:
S L O P E
A slope in the backyard can take up a lot of space that might not be functional. You can utilize retaining walls to push back the soil and create more space to make it more useable.
.
At this property we pushed the slope back 20’ to create space for a pool, guest house and outdoor kitchen. Then we utilize the height of the retaining wall to create a tall waterfeature. Win-win for creating the retaining wall.
.
Who wants to hangout at this pool?
.
📲contact us @dannywangdesign for your interior exterior design build needs
.
.
.

.

node.text:
W A P (Wrap Around Pool)
This plot was narrow but required some some creativity to put a pool in. So the pool was wrapped around the house to make it more usable.
.
1 side of the pool consist of pilasters with firebowl atop. The other side was custom designed arches with the lion head and water spill through the arches.
.
Then the pool was finished with thousands of mosaic to create this beautiful and exquisite look.
.
Which side of the WAP do you like the best? 
.
By @designsbydannywang

node.text:
N A R R O W
This backyard was a challenging yard because it was very narrow yet long. We decided to section the yard into multiple functional areas.
.
The first third we built a floating pad surrounded by water for a place to do yoga or meditate with the fountain walls.
.
The second area was a zero edge pool with a sunken fire pit next to the pool house. What is unique about this pool house is we put a spa under the roof so people can use the spa out of direct sunlight.
.
The third area we incorporated a circular rose garden with a checkered pattern pathway leading up to the iron gazebo.
.
One yard but multi functional. Which area is your favorite?
.
Design @designsbydannywang
.

.
.
.
.
.
